  Netty 4.2 and Unsafe Netty 4.2.0 and 4.2.1 take no special precautions, and produce warnings the same as Netty 4.1 (excluding 4.1.120 and 4.1.121) does. Netty 4.2.2 and newer adds support for using MemorySegment APIs to avoid relying on Unsafe . The memory segment support comes in two variants: Preferred: Linking directly to the system malloc and free functions. ( PR #15366 ) This mechanism is supported from Java 24 onwards, but it requires native access to be enabled. To enable native access, the JVM must be launched with this command line argument: --enable-native-access=io.netty.common This mechanism is available since Netty 4.2.3. This mechanism is the preferred way, because it has the least amount of overhead when allocating and deallocating. Fallback: Using shared memory segment arenas. ( PR #15231 ) This mechanism does not require native access. However, due to JDK bugs, it can only be used from Java 25 onwards ( PR #15338 ) This mechanism is available since Netty 4.2.2. This mechanism is the last resort fall-back because it does not require native access. However, releasing shared arenas is expensive because it involves thread-local handshakes (a cheaper form of safepoint) and JIT de-optimization. What Netty uses Unsafe for Netty and its native transports need native (off-heap) memory to move data faster to and from the operating system, i.e. without copying data into and out of the heap as well. To effectively work with native memory, Netty needs a way to not only allocate memory, but also deallocate it as soon as it's done using it. Netty needs Unsafe to access the cleaner instance inside the direct ByteBuffers . The cleaner is the mechanism used to deallocate the memory in direct ByteBuffer instances. When Unsafe is not available to Netty, then the ByteBuffer
[tool-exec] end id=call_is3Yxuqfgfft3msTM4kXjHrF|fc_07b2e1eb058c915e016a3e71dedfb48194aef2ea5da7868a72 name=bash status=success
